text: I will only watch war movies to witness the sacrifice so many young men made. Young men, in most cases, of meager means.  The rich, who created these wars, were not sending their kids to the battle field.  If people knew the truth behind these wars, which were wars of supremacy and class structures that used the masses as disposable pawns or batteries for their war efforts. Under the auspices of fighting a foreign enemy from abroad. As the former 4th US President said, _"If men were angels, no government would be necessary. _*_If¬†Tyranny¬†and Oppression come to this land, it will be in the guise of fighting a foreign enemy._*_ It is a universal truth that the loss of liberty at home is to be charged to the provisions against danger, real or pretended, from abroad."_  And now, Hollywood is profiting from those sacrifices.  If the profits, even 50% went to the families of the fallen soldiers, I would have no problem.  But we all know that won't happen...

text: There's a new WWI movie coming out. And my spidey sense says it's going to be trash.    In the trailer:    >You must deliver a message to tell them they're walking into a trap. If you don't, 1,600 men will die.    Lads. This was WWI. 1,600 soldiers is nothing and makes me think the director must not have a grasp of the terrifically grand scale of WWI.    >Battle of Arras: 278,000 casualties  Battles of Tannenberg & Masurian Lakes: 347,000 casualties  >Second Battle of the Aisne: 355,000 Casualties  >Battle of Kolubara: 405,000 casualties  >Gallipoli campaign: 470,000 casualties  >First Battle of the Marne: 519,000 casualties  >Battle of Galicia: 655,0000 casualties  >Battle of Verdun: 698,000 casualties  >Battle of Lys and Second Battle of the Somme: 191 ‚Äì 804,100 casualties  >Third Battle of Ypres: 857,100 casualties  >Gorlice-Tarn√≥w Offensive: 1,087,000 casualties  >First Battle of the Somme: 1,113,000 casualties  >Spring Offensive: 1,539,715 casualties  >Hundred Days Offensive: 1,855,369 Casualties  >Brusilov Offensive: 2,317,800 casualties    With battles like these, absolute hellscape meat grinders we can't even comprehend, why would a director make a WWI movie where saving 1,600 soldiers is portrayed as some grand thing?    I feel like it doesn't capture the gravity of WWI at all.

text: Sadly I feel like they're going to bastardise any and all historical accuracy for the sake of making a Hollywood "Blockbuster"   I'm not saying a movie like this needs to strictly adhere to every historical event and detail, but when Universal and Dreamworks both get involved I feel like anything and everything is free game to change in order to suit audience expectations of a big budget action movie.    Sam Mendes is also a supremely average director. He doesn't have a particularly discernible style and manages to somehow circumvent a lot criticism by attaching himself to projects that already have established places in pop culture. Critics will most likely give this a 6 or 7 out of 10 because it's one of the few WW1 films made within the last 70 years and will be more entertaining for a mass audience than the other previous interpretations of the war.    I'd like it to be good, but the trailer isn't filling me with much hope.

text: World War 1 doesn't seem to get the respect it should. World War 2 always has overshadowed the history of the first. That may be because WW1 led to WW2 but WW1 was unlike any other war we have seen. It was unique in the sense that it was so terrible and such a meat grinder of men that many of the tactics were not to be repeated. The stagnant lines, the gas attacks, heavy entrenchments, year long battles over miles of wasteland, and initial use of air and vehicle tactics. It all made for some of the heaviest and to be quite honest, unreasonable losses the world has ever seen. I have always wished they made more movies on WW1. Those who are interested I suggest you take a trip to visit the battlefield of Verdun which has much of the remnants of the battle intact. The ground is full of craters from the battle. My family went because my great grandfather fought there and wrote about the gas attacks. He survived the battle and the rest of the war only to die from the removal of a wisdom tooth and infection. We can only imagine what they went through.

text: Unfortunately, this film is propaganda and distorted, and it is the historical revisionism film.  In the reality, my young twenty-one years old grandfather served for the US Army artillery unit, and fought in the World War One on the front line in France.  He seriously wounded twice (the artillery barrage that killed all of his crew mate except him (badly injured his legs), and he also, was caught by mustard gas.   He survived nightmarish with severe coughing with blood.  He endured with his scarred lung with minor cough for a rest of his life, but he was a happy successful man with his supportive wife.  He was 87 years old when he died.  He was one of the true military heroes to serve the country and fought for the freedom.   Today, younger generation failed to understand this horror reality in a war, and patriotism of the country because of the  propagandized historical revisionism and political correctness are distorted by leftist cultural Marxism running Hollywood film industries that indoctrinated young generations to reject the realism and historical facts.

text: In 2 years, we have 2 excellent films based on WWI. Last year, the documentary They Shall Not Grow Old, and now the upcoming 1917, which looks amazing already. There's kind of a personal stake in this when I go see it.   My great-great grandpa actually fought in this conflict. Now, he did fight for the Germans but he was not down for the cause of the leaders. He simply fought for the country because he loved it. During this time, though, a major battle was raging. He, and I'm sure a few other men, had to pull back cannons from No Man's Land to behind their lines. Anyone that knows about WWI history, No Man's Land was basically a death trap. My great-great grandpa made it and was awarded the Iron Cross. That's quite the honor, I would say. He did immigrate over here to the states after the war and the first generation in the US, of my mom's side of the family, was born. One of grandpa's cousins today still has the Iron Cross that my great-great grandpa was awarded 100 years ago.   Seeing this and They Shall Not Grow Old, although they're both told from the British's perspective, is a reminder to me of what my ancestor had to go through. This was a war that could have been avoided and it very well could have prevented WWII, a much bloodier and larger conflict, from ever happening. However, that is debatable and Europe was going through massive economic changes. Either way, WWI history is just as fascinating as WWII's history. If anyone is wants to get a taste of it, I would encourage anyone here to watch They Shall Not Grow Old. If you haven't heard of it, the documentary uses actual footage of the events that occurred while all in color and adding voices and sound effects to the once silent films. It tells the story from the soldiers' point of view, everything that they had to endure. Then go see this when it hits. I know I will.

text: This movie is trying to be Dunkirk WAY too hard. The music is the most obvious giveaway with that ticking sound lol, the long takes and chase cams trying to make the action scenes more suspenseful but it feels and looks less quality. It just feels so flat or ‚Äústaged‚Äù where as Dunkirk felt real. The opening running scene for example just feels like a set in a field without any relevance or impact other than lets throw in some well placed explosions. And the camera quality makes the subject pop out way too much, it looks almost fakish. This era of directors really have lost their ability to make the visuals match the story. Everything is about shooting high res for no reason. It actually makes movies look bad, and staged. Super 65 is high res but its a format that has flexibility with its depth. Smaller sensor cameras just compensate for sharpness and it brings way too much of the scene into focus. Looks cheap.

text: Lol, literally everything looks...wrong. Everybody are clean like they are at historical reenactment meeting and not war. WWI was famously known for it's absolutely abysmal conditions in trenches. Puddles, mud, waste, rats, smell. Trenches all look clinically clean. In the first scene they are running over a pristine field that hasn't seen a single artillery shell. Now, it's possible that's the first action this field has. However, it's unlikely since soldiers are charging. Overall, it looks like you expect Hollywood movie about war to look - wrong. I'm still interested since movies about WWI are far and few between, especially high profile ones. Not having much faith in it though.

text: Ok, so they have a battalion, the size of a regiment, which is still on it's initial position, preparing for an attack. It's not somewhere in a desert, out in a wild, or something. It's the Western Front, 1917. When each freaking company had a field telephone, connected at least to the battalion HQ and the battalion HQ connected to the command telephone network through several lines. And even if all those lines were severed by a heavy shelling or enemy saboteurs, there still should be another unit, next to the battalion in question, which can be contacted by phone and the messenger sent from it, instead of sending a messengers from somewhere far-far away with as low, as possible chance of success. I am all for a good war movie, but come on, why not make the story believable? There are so many REAL war stories, that are way cooler then any of your stupid super-hero-drama crap. Why not use those?

text: ...another awful film pandering to someone's cinematic notion of what warfare is. This time it's set in the 1914-18 period,  for no other reason, than to place the plot cinematically, if not tragically. Charging over an open field, with not a spool of defensive barbed wire in sight, is some director's idea of capturing the futility of war. Peter Jackson's wonderful work of doctoring original first world war footage, has spoilt it for us. These are real participants in a tragic episode of world history, not male extras hired for the movie, who all look like models. Following in the footsteps of Dunkirk. An equally pointless movie, with enough Hollywood fabrication to destroy any belief, that a war movie can be made without being spoilt by poor editing and equally poor storyline. Maybe Danger Close, can save the day.

text: Trench warfare is one of the nastiest forms of battle we've engaged in. They were filled with vermin and disease. A psychological battle of attrition, with little yields over expensure. It became obsolete due to the first tanks being used.  It was at this time when they coined the term "shell shocked", which later became known as PTSD. We were first-hand witnessing the horrors of war on a massive, relentless scale. The further development of weapons, artillery, aircraft, and chemical warfare. Respects to those brave soldiers (people like you and I) who served and who were thrown into the face of adversity. May we never forget those who have layed down their life for us, and our respective idealogies.

text: this movie is so bad, the director should be court-martialled resulting in field punishment no.1! Such horrible production design, it's an abomination to all ww1 enthusiasts. The trenches and noman's land look like the war had just begun, and it's supposed to be 1917!? Thick foliage on the trees all around , helloooo???? Have you ever cared to research the effects of heavy artillery for weeks on end? Virtually cricket field Standard lawns in noman's land?!? WTF?! This makes me really mad. WW1 has so many good stories still to be told for the big screen, and this is another weak result. Sam Mendez, stick to James Bond and leave the real wars to those who really care about history. This is poor attempt of Story telling, not forgetting the unvelievably unsurprising and boring plot line a la "Saving Private Ryan" meets  "Journey's End". This is far worse than "Companions", not only because Spielberg wasn't involved, thank the Lord, but because there isn't even a cheesy love Story interwoven with the sickeningly predictable Story.
